DictKey_descriptionBlueTask_3:
VF-32: Gypsy-2 (Chevy-2)

Sortie for today will be a combat air patrol 100 miles to the east of the Kennedy battle group. VF-14, Gypsy-1 (Chevy-1) will accompany a flight of A-6E Intruders on a training exercise to Crete. You are to provide air cover to the southeast of them. 

Since the discovery of the chemical weapons manufacturing facility Gadaffi recently commissioned near Rabta, tensions between Nato and Libya have once again begun to flare up and we can only assume that our presence in the region will have the Lybian's on edge. So you can probably expect the usual incursions by snooping LAF aircraft. 

As to not cause a repeat of the '81 incident, the Admiralty has issued new orders stating that any Libyan fighters which attempt three or more deliberate intercept maneuvers on USN aircraft, are to be declared hostile and engaged if they refuse to turn cold once painted by radar.  

Once airborne, rendezvous with Arco 1-1 and top off your tanks, then proceed directly to waypoint 2 to begin your patrol to the south. Remain in the area until Dodge is on the return leg of their training exercise, whereupon you can depart west back for the boat.

Good luck! 

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

CV-67 (59) - USS John F. Kennedy / Wingman
Radio Ch:1 -225MHz AM
TACAN: 11X (Preset)
ICLS: 7 (Preset)
Recovery Heading: 033°

AWACS - E-2D Hawkeye 
Magic 1-1
Radio Ch: 2 - 258MHz AM

Tanker - S-3B Viking
Arco 1-1
Radio Ch: 3 - 260MHz AM
TACAN: 41X

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Mission Hints:


Follow your instruction prompts! Failing to do so will result in mission failure or the bandits turning cold and running for home.

Occasionally your wingman has a tendency to get stuck on deck, so wait for launch authorization before taking off. If it still happens, unfortunately, "Shift R" is your only recourse. 

Pay close attention to your flight parameters once the intercept begins. You will be punished for not watching your speed and altitude!   

Don't touch your weapons or master arm unless given express permission by your RIO to do so. 

Don't try to rearm before launch, it won't help you! Your current loadout is historically accurate and mission-specific. Changing your missiles will break triggers, so you'll have to spam Pheonix's another day I'm afraid...

Refueling is not essential, however, you will have to manage your gas well if you don't intend on swimming home. 

When tanking, don't forget to put your probe switch to its most upper position, or your drop tanks will remain empty.

The tanker will continue to orbit along its east-west track until you return to the boat, so you can always top up your tanks on the return leg home if need be. 

Remember to order your wingman to refuel once you've topped off your tanks. You'll have about 15 minutes to get gas before you reach waypoint 2.

Fly your waypoints accurately and conduct any maneuvers during the intercept smoothly. No need to bank harder than 2 or 3G. Turning through your desired heading too quickly can negate a trigger from activating. 

Wait for your next text message before conducting your next maneuver. If you're having trouble setting off the next trigger, try turning a few degrees left or right of your designated heading. It can, however, take a moment before the next trigger activates, so remain on course for 15-20 seconds before correcting your track. You'll have approximately 60 seconds to execute each maneuver.

Hold down your trigger for at least a second when firing missiles. There is a tendency to skip audio files if pressed too quickly.  

You won't need to hear Jester for this mission, so you can mute him any time after launch... Unless you like being laughed at whilst tanking anyway. 

Try not to get target fixated. Always follow your prompts and continue on to your designated heading until you receive launch authorization.

Once you have launch authorization, what your wingman does is up to you - Don't forget to issue him attack orders via F10.

If you do everything right, you should get accurate radar contacts and end up in more or less the same position as Gypsy-2 when they engaged the Libyan MiGs at a range of 12 miles...

Have Fun!

Ozone.
DictKey_descriptionText_1:
The day is January 4, 1989.

Four F-14A's from USS John F. Kennedy (CV-67) fly a mission as Combat Air Patrol in support of several A-6E Intruders on a planned exercise, south of Crete. The first pair of Tomcats from VF-14 escorted the A-6's while the second pair of F-14's from VF-32 provided cover to the southeast of the strike group. 

Suddenly a pair of Libyan Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-23 Floggers were detected at long range by an E-2C Hawkeye from VAW-126, providing airborne early warning and control to the task force.

The MiG-23s had taken off from Al Bumbaw Airfield near Tobruk and they continued their flight towards the US fighters, even though they had been locked up by the F-14s radar.

It's a common procedure under such circumstances to lock the powerful AWG-9 radar on the incoming Libyan fighters, to give them the possibility to turn around and head back home.

Usually, this procedure was impressive enough to drive the Libyans back since the radar warning tone resulting from an armed F-14's radar was fearsome enough.

But this time it did not work. For the second time in less than a decade, US Navy F-14s were engaged by Libyan fighter aircraft under hostile conditions.

During the 8 minute engagement, the MiGs kept turning in on the Tomcats to maintain a firing solution for their Soviet-built air-to-air missiles.

As later examination of F-14 still photography revealed, the MiG-23s were armed with AA-7 Apex missiles.

After several evasive maneuvers by the Tomcats and aggressive maneuvers by the Floggers, the incoming pair of MiG-23s were declared hostile and the F-14 crews were cleared to engage at a range of 12 miles.

The crew of the lead F-14A, (AC207) fired an unsuccessful AIM-7M Sparrow missile, while the second 
F-14A's (AC202) AIM-7 found its target and destroyed one of the MiGs at a range of 5 miles.

Thereafter, the lead F-14 closed in on the remaining Flogger and launched an AIM-9L Sidewinder heat-seeking missile.

The missile exploded in the tailpipe of the fleeing MiG, forcing its pilot to eject from his destroyed aircraft into the Mediterranean Sea.

Both MiG pilots were seen with good chutes, however, it is not known whether the Libyan Air Force was able to successfully recover either of them.

After the engagement, the victorious Tomcats headed north for the carrier and a heros welcome...
